1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,140
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassam

2
00:00:18,323 --> 00:00:31,359
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,563 --> 00:00:40,609
I'm just wondering whether there's a question somebody has which I can hinge my talk on.

4
00:00:43,634 --> 00:00:47,097
It always produces a sort of dead silence.

5
00:00:48,799 --> 00:00:53,786
There might be something on somebody's mind that they're wondering about the Buddha's teachings.

6
00:01:06,462 --> 00:01:11,968
Could you possibly speak a little bit about things not having an inherent existence?

7
00:01:12,269 --> 00:01:17,676
Ah, the old inherent existence.

8
00:01:18,635 --> 00:01:24,781
This is very much a Mahayana way of expressing things.

9
00:01:25,722 --> 00:01:41,521
It's basically saying that everything is contingent, everything is dependent on everything else, or on something else, which is dependent on something else, dependent on something else, so that you end up with a world which is just completely interconnected.

10
00:01:42,763 --> 00:01:45,305
And therefore, nothing has its own being.

11
00:01:46,387 --> 00:01:48,168
Nothing can exist completely on its own.

12
00:01:48,469 --> 00:01:52,674
So you can't take anything out of this universe and expect it to exist.

13
00:01:53,656 --> 00:01:55,477
It'll just disappear or whatever.

14
00:01:56,838 --> 00:02:05,128
And when we take that into ourselves, you see, that's where it begins to undermine this idea of who I am.

15
00:02:05,168 --> 00:02:09,352
So just consider all your thoughts.

16
00:02:14,037 --> 00:02:18,342
Have you ever had an original thought, a thought which has never been thought before?

17
00:02:21,393 --> 00:02:26,038
I mean, occasionally you do get a human being who comes up with an original thought.

18
00:02:26,058 --> 00:02:30,004
I mean, somebody must have discovered the wheel, I suppose, at some point.

19
00:02:31,486 --> 00:02:36,052
But most of our thoughts are just rehashing of thoughts that have been given to us.

20
00:02:36,933 --> 00:02:41,539
I mean, they do have, of course, a twist of our own personality and experience.

21
00:02:42,442 --> 00:02:47,247
But all our thinking is dependent on the language we've been taught.

22
00:02:47,937 --> 00:02:52,102
And through the language, whatever information has come to us.

23
00:02:53,062 --> 00:03:09,842
So one of the little conceits that we suffer from is that, you know, my thoughts are particularly, one of the conceits we can suffer from is that, you know, I've had this amazing thought and it's absolutely original.

24
00:03:10,602 --> 00:03:12,003
Nobody else thinks like me.

25
00:03:13,317 --> 00:03:18,342
And then you write your book and you find that lots of other people have written similar things.

26
00:03:19,425 --> 00:03:33,122
So there's nothing which isn't dependent on something else, which hasn't arisen because of some other influence.

27
00:03:33,143 --> 00:03:37,608
Our emotional life is always dependent on something, isn't it?

28
00:03:37,627 --> 00:03:41,973
You're always happy about something or sad about something else.

29
00:03:42,814 --> 00:03:46,860
You can't have an emotion which isn't about something.

30
00:03:47,881 --> 00:03:50,183
Can you?

31
00:03:50,424 --> 00:03:52,947
It's difficult anyway.

32
00:03:53,247 --> 00:03:59,694
It's always dependent on some sort of stimulus, something out there, or some history within ourselves.

33
00:04:02,078 --> 00:04:04,980
We have a history within ourselves of experience.

34
00:04:05,001 --> 00:04:09,986
So when it comes back to us as a memory, it will bring up some sort of emotional sense.

35
00:04:12,058 --> 00:04:14,382
The body, of course, is even more obvious.

36
00:04:14,401 --> 00:04:25,834
The body is entirely dependent on carrots, cabbage, and the air we breathe.

37
00:04:26,574 --> 00:04:28,317
We're one breath away from death.

38
00:04:32,701 --> 00:04:36,125
So that sense of interdependency,

39
00:04:37,507 --> 00:04:50,223
getting away the idea that we often feel that I'm a very individual, distinct person, and I do my own thing in my own way, in my own time.

40
00:04:50,262 --> 00:05:00,055
Now that very sort of more American and European, I think, idea of that, the success that I've had in this world is all due to me.

41
00:05:01,468 --> 00:05:04,894
Mind all the workers and everybody who's put that input in.

42
00:05:05,374 --> 00:05:08,218
If it weren't for me, I wouldn't be a multimillionaire.

43
00:05:08,237 --> 00:05:09,279
I wouldn't be a billionaire.

44
00:05:09,439 --> 00:05:10,982
I did it all, all by myself.

45
00:05:11,543 --> 00:05:13,906
What's the name of that woman that wrote something about that?

46
00:05:14,266 --> 00:05:16,108
She was into that sort of ideology.

47
00:05:19,413 --> 00:05:19,795
What is it?

48
00:05:19,814 --> 00:05:20,415
Oh, dear me.

49
00:05:20,795 --> 00:05:23,680
She was a Russian emigre in America.

50
00:05:25,026 --> 00:05:27,312
Yeah, young man, you see.

51
00:05:27,995 --> 00:05:37,021
And all these people, all these, because I saw a program, you know, because of my memory, I can't remember it, but there's a little bit, I'll forget of it, not memory.

52
00:05:37,963 --> 00:05:39,507
And because of this...

53
00:05:41,547 --> 00:05:45,793
Because of this, Ian, what's her name?

54
00:05:45,812 --> 00:05:46,353
Ian, no.

55
00:05:47,394 --> 00:05:49,718
Anne, Anne, Anne.

56
00:05:50,639 --> 00:06:01,254
They interviewed people who had these big, you know, multi, these California, very successful businesses, IT businesses.

57
00:06:01,274 --> 00:06:04,899
And there was one man, he said, you know, he just felt completely empowered.

58
00:06:05,399 --> 00:06:10,406
And he was of the opinion that this whole empire that he built was entirely for him.

59
00:06:10,622 --> 00:06:11,745
He'd done it.

60
00:06:11,766 --> 00:06:23,399
So there's that sort of egotistical, very self-centered idea that we can suffer from when we don't see our interdependency.

61
00:06:24,612 --> 00:06:31,302
Another way of saying that we're interdependent is this business of inherent.

62
00:06:31,442 --> 00:06:34,887
We're not inherently independent.

63
00:06:35,348 --> 00:06:37,290
We can't exist on our own, full stop.

64
00:06:37,692 --> 00:06:40,817
Now, all that is around the teaching of not-self, you see.

65
00:06:42,418 --> 00:06:43,521
All around that, not-self.

66
00:06:44,002 --> 00:06:48,949
Now, how does it happen that we end up with these sorts of...

67
00:06:50,482 --> 00:06:51,242
delusions.

68
00:06:52,944 --> 00:06:57,271
Eastern people are still much more community-based.

69
00:07:00,233 --> 00:07:10,487
The Chinese, the Burmese, they still have a sense of me being part of a community, me being just part of something bigger than me.

70
00:07:11,148 --> 00:07:18,598
There isn't that severe individual separation between me and the rest.

71
00:07:19,978 --> 00:07:28,250
Now this deep delusion as to who we are is the core of our problem in the Buddha's understanding.

72
00:07:28,271 --> 00:07:35,281
It's to do with identity, to do with really beginning to investigate this sense of I.

73
00:07:37,144 --> 00:07:47,319
Now we talked about that a little bit this morning, but in a sense you have to understand that what the I does mean is it creates a relationship to the world.

74
00:07:47,670 --> 00:07:55,762
So the desire for happiness, the desire for happiness is coming from the Buddha within.

75
00:07:56,483 --> 00:07:58,487
It's the Buddha within that wants to be happy.

76
00:07:59,528 --> 00:08:00,971
It's not a mental thing.

77
00:08:01,732 --> 00:08:10,185
It expresses itself as a mental thing because we express that desire for happiness in wanting things, in wanting fame and relationships and all that.

78
00:08:10,603 --> 00:08:15,408
But the deep desire for happiness is coming from this Buddha within.

79
00:08:16,350 --> 00:08:22,177
I say Buddha within because it's not quite the Buddha yet, it's the Bodhisattva, it's still deluded.

80
00:08:24,079 --> 00:08:29,324
And it's found itself in this psychophysical organism.

81
00:08:30,185 --> 00:08:32,488
Now the Buddha doesn't go into the whys of that.

82
00:08:32,989 --> 00:08:35,951
He's not interested in why should that happen.

83
00:08:36,513 --> 00:08:40,256
He's not interested in some sort of metaphysics.

84
00:08:41,265 --> 00:08:43,068
He's only interested in how.

85
00:08:44,910 --> 00:08:46,894
How does it happen that we're unhappy?

86
00:08:46,994 --> 00:08:55,567
How does it happen that we are chasing these dragons that don't actually exist or at least won't deliver the happiness that we want?

87
00:08:56,187 --> 00:09:01,976
And it all comes back to this fundamental basic position of not knowing, not knowing.

88
00:09:02,576 --> 00:09:04,320
Now, in Dependent Originations,

89
00:09:04,739 --> 00:09:07,442
which is the psychological teaching of the Buddha.

90
00:09:07,802 --> 00:09:10,565
It begins with that word, avijja, not knowing.

91
00:09:11,285 --> 00:09:16,230
It's often translated as ignorance, which gives it a sort of culpability, you know, like you're ignorant.

92
00:09:16,932 --> 00:09:18,033
But that's not the meaning of it.

93
00:09:18,113 --> 00:09:19,534
It's just simply don't know.

94
00:09:19,554 --> 00:09:23,099
And we're born into this form.

95
00:09:23,759 --> 00:09:28,004
When I say we, I mean that Buddha within is born into this form.

96
00:09:28,024 --> 00:09:30,746
And it's not surprising that it should completely identify with

97
00:09:31,687 --> 00:09:47,985
So here it is, a screaming little baby, and it hurts, and sometimes it's happy, and there's an unexpressed and unreflective identity with it, and that stays with us for most people until they die.

98
00:09:48,366 --> 00:09:49,288
I am this body.

99
00:09:51,250 --> 00:10:00,801
If we understood, if we really, really understood that I am not this body, then we wouldn't be shaken by sickness or by death.

100
00:10:01,945 --> 00:10:11,099
So the fear of death and the anger around it and the grief around it are measures of this identity that we have with the body.

101
00:10:13,461 --> 00:10:31,107
So once we have this identity of the self, once we have this body, this person that I am, which includes the body, the mind, the heart, the whole psychophysical organism, once I've identified that and I'm seeking happiness, then

102
00:10:31,678 --> 00:10:33,360
You know, what is it that makes me happy?

103
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:35,442
It's the accumulation of things.

104
00:10:35,462 --> 00:10:39,145
The more I accumulate, the happier I am.

105
00:10:39,506 --> 00:10:42,889
So, you know, to have lots of money makes me happy.

106
00:10:43,250 --> 00:10:47,293
But to have billions of it, really, that makes me feel very safe.

107
00:10:48,855 --> 00:10:50,977
I'd have to do something terrible to lose billions.

108
00:10:51,658 --> 00:10:52,578
I might not spend it.

109
00:10:52,919 --> 00:10:53,659
That's irrelevant.

110
00:10:54,140 --> 00:10:56,783
I can do anything I want with all my billions.

111
00:10:56,923 --> 00:11:00,386
But the fact is that makes me feel safe.

112
00:11:00,433 --> 00:11:18,815
Now, that's the underlying psychology that, should we say, subsists underneath all our gathering and acquisitiveness, our greed and lust and all that sort of stuff, is the fact that there's a deep sense of insecurity.

113
00:11:20,777 --> 00:11:30,187
That deep sense of insecurity manifests every time the body falls ill or somebody we know dies, and it sort of cuts into us, you see?

114
00:11:30,421 --> 00:11:34,384
Now we have to cover that insecurity up because it's not a pleasant place to be.

115
00:11:34,924 --> 00:11:44,975
And we do it by accumulating wealth, accumulating friendships, accumulating spiritual highs.

116
00:11:44,995 --> 00:11:50,639
It's very comforting to think that I'm an amazingly good meditator.

117
00:11:50,659 --> 00:11:57,626
So any way that we can cushion ourselves against this whole business of insecurity,

118
00:11:58,096 --> 00:12:00,620
becomes that acquisitiveness.

119
00:12:01,341 --> 00:12:06,847
Now, once you've got something, you have to protect it.

120
00:12:07,129 --> 00:12:08,389
You have to protect it against enemies.

121
00:12:09,030 --> 00:12:10,312
Enemies who want what you've got.

122
00:12:11,153 --> 00:12:13,878
So we do it through aversion.

123
00:12:13,898 --> 00:12:17,062
We try to get rid of things that are threatening us.

124
00:12:18,283 --> 00:12:19,725
At worst, murder, of course.

125
00:12:20,147 --> 00:12:23,451
But simple things like jealousies.

126
00:12:24,011 --> 00:12:25,875
Jealousies, envies.

127
00:12:26,698 --> 00:12:34,553
Those little ways that we see that our fame or what we are, what we've accumulated isn't as good as somebody else's.

128
00:12:34,894 --> 00:12:38,561
So we're constantly trying to make myself feel more and more safe.

129
00:12:39,602 --> 00:12:47,457
And anything that threatens me, anything that threatens my accumulations, I see them as enemies and I have to get rid of them one way or the other.

130
00:12:48,822 --> 00:13:03,399
If, of course, it all gets too heavy, if the enemy is right on top of me and I can't escape the enemy, then my escape route is to turn inward with the hatred and I end up committing suicide.

131
00:13:03,519 --> 00:13:08,846
So these two poles of the enemy create both the aversion and the fear.

132
00:13:09,807 --> 00:13:10,648
So there we have it.

133
00:13:10,668 --> 00:13:18,356
That's the basic platform of our delusive relationship to the world, coming from a wrong identity of who I am.

134
00:13:18,826 --> 00:13:22,548
I'm trying to accumulate things to make myself feel safe.

135
00:13:22,568 --> 00:13:28,793
I'm averse to anything that threatens that sense of safety, which is created by these accumulations.

136
00:13:29,735 --> 00:13:32,957
And when it gets too much, I'm going to run for it.

137
00:13:33,518 --> 00:13:34,178
I'm going to hide.

138
00:13:34,239 --> 00:13:38,042
I'm going to find a cave, somewhere to disappear into.

139
00:13:39,062 --> 00:13:48,410
Now, that basis then, what it does is it begins to manifest in the way we think, in the way we speak, in the way we act.

140
00:13:48,745 --> 00:13:53,710
And that's when the ethical life comes into existence.

141
00:13:54,870 --> 00:14:08,043
So just to separate out morality from ethics, morality meaning these sort of basic rules that presumably most of us in this room now generally keep, murdering and feeding.

142
00:14:09,283 --> 00:14:11,986
Ethics is a much broader concept of relationship.

143
00:14:12,888 --> 00:14:16,490
So what is our relationship to other human beings?

144
00:14:16,792 --> 00:14:18,975
What is our relationship to the animal world?

145
00:14:19,495 --> 00:14:23,400
What is our relationship to the world of plants, even to the world of minerals?

146
00:14:23,520 --> 00:14:24,962
What's our relationship?

147
00:14:24,982 --> 00:14:26,806
That was the old medieval, wasn't it?

148
00:14:26,826 --> 00:14:29,168
Minerals, plants, animals and human beings.

149
00:14:29,188 --> 00:14:32,013
There's your four kingdoms, as they were called.

150
00:14:32,173 --> 00:14:35,798
So what's our relationship to that, you see?

151
00:14:35,817 --> 00:14:43,508
And when we begin to investigate that, we find that it's really all there to serve its means.

152
00:14:44,753 --> 00:14:48,116
Because I'm constantly trying to feel safe.

153
00:14:48,616 --> 00:14:50,839
And I feel safe by making myself happy.

154
00:14:51,440 --> 00:14:53,721
And it's me who defines what makes me happy.

155
00:14:54,202 --> 00:14:55,303
So it might be riches.

156
00:14:55,403 --> 00:14:56,544
It might be fame.

157
00:14:58,246 --> 00:15:04,494
It might be anything which draws me into my happiness and makes me feel safe.

158
00:15:05,333 --> 00:15:14,524
So that's what happens when this sense of I, this sense of me being a person, an individual in the world,

159
00:15:16,039 --> 00:15:19,104
That's how we begin to relate to it.

160
00:15:19,926 --> 00:15:26,855
Now, our personalities and characters are not all like that.

161
00:15:26,875 --> 00:15:31,883
Part of it, of course, is driven by love, compassion, sympathetic joy, and all the rest of it.

162
00:15:33,245 --> 00:15:37,490
And it's beginning to realize that actually that's where our true safety lies.

163
00:15:38,298 --> 00:15:52,037
Our true safety lies in really facing up to the reality of life, which is about growing old and sick and dying and all that, and to begin to relate to people in a slightly different way.

164
00:15:52,817 --> 00:15:57,184
And that different way is this business of interconnectedness.

165
00:15:57,205 --> 00:16:02,432
So when we talk about interconnectedness at a heart level, all we talk about is love.

166
00:16:03,205 --> 00:16:05,169
Love, which is friendship.

167
00:16:06,413 --> 00:16:13,049
Compassion, which is that movement in the heart which wants to help somebody who's in some sort of difficulty or pain.

168
00:16:14,072 --> 00:16:19,527
And compassion itself is not a painful state.

169
00:16:20,400 --> 00:16:29,895
I was at this center and they came up to me and they said, we've decided that the Buddha couldn't be compassionate.

170
00:16:30,616 --> 00:16:33,802
I said, oh, I said, why is that?

171
00:16:33,822 --> 00:16:34,663
Because he'd be suffering.

172
00:16:35,344 --> 00:16:36,225
Because he'd be suffering.

173
00:16:36,505 --> 00:16:38,428
If he was compassionate, he'd be suffering.

174
00:16:38,448 --> 00:16:42,595
That's a completely confusion between compassion and grief.

175
00:16:43,620 --> 00:16:48,027
Grief is when we have pity on somebody.

176
00:16:48,727 --> 00:16:56,057
Grief is what we feel when we've lost something personal, when it's some attachment that goes.

177
00:16:57,198 --> 00:17:00,143
But compassion is a joyful thing.

178
00:17:00,484 --> 00:17:05,190
Compassion raises great joy in the heart when you're helping somebody.

179
00:17:07,009 --> 00:17:14,699
So that when you're helping somebody and you feel some sort of grief for them, that's coming from that sense of pity.

180
00:17:17,842 --> 00:17:23,749
So all these beautiful states like love, compassion, sympathy, joy, they're in us too.

181
00:17:24,410 --> 00:17:33,539
And as we move along the spiritual path, part of it is the happiness, the ordinary human happiness.

182
00:17:34,329 --> 00:17:36,672
So the Buddha talks about going from darkness to light.

183
00:17:37,353 --> 00:17:46,021
And part of the training, half of the training, is to do with ethics, is to do with developing the beautiful side of our personalities.

184
00:17:46,423 --> 00:17:51,407
And in so doing, we find ourselves much more at home in the world, much more connected.

185
00:17:52,890 --> 00:17:55,291
And in that, of course, the safety.

186
00:17:55,772 --> 00:18:02,700
The safety, the lack of the fear of insecurity comes because we don't accept the insecurity of life.

187
00:18:03,220 --> 00:18:08,126
But once you accept the insecurity of life, you undermine the fear of insecurity.

188
00:18:08,146 --> 00:18:09,388
There is insecurity.

189
00:18:09,608 --> 00:18:10,730
There's not much you can do about it.

190
00:18:12,773 --> 00:18:27,355
So part of our spiritual life is the cleansing of that, the purification of the heart, based on the wrong understanding of habits that we've developed because of these wrong understandings.

191
00:18:29,308 --> 00:18:30,391
unwholesome habits.

192
00:18:30,411 --> 00:18:34,680
So this word akusala translated as unskillful, unwholesome.

193
00:18:35,883 --> 00:18:38,587
But the other side is the development of the beautiful heart.

194
00:18:40,271 --> 00:18:45,884
And it's slowly moving in that direction which is part and parcel of the process.

195
00:18:45,903 --> 00:18:48,869
Now when it comes to this identity, the self,

196
00:18:49,896 --> 00:18:57,769
It's much easier to drop the self when the heart is pure than when it's not pure.

197
00:18:57,788 --> 00:19:04,358
If you're very angry with somebody, it's very difficult to say, well, I'm not angry, there is anger.

198
00:19:07,522 --> 00:19:18,519
But when you're actually moving from the position of love, it's easier to let go of this self-centeredness because the other is your center of attention.

199
00:19:20,051 --> 00:19:29,840
It's much easier to let go of me, me, me all the time when you're in a compassionate relationship with somebody who's suffering because they are the focus of your attention, not you.

200
00:19:32,303 --> 00:19:41,692
So that whole movement away from what is negative within us to what is positive is something that we can actually do, that we can actually practice.

201
00:19:42,551 --> 00:19:48,657
And by simply every day just giving ourselves a little task,

202
00:19:49,111 --> 00:19:54,999
For instance, there was an occasion when the Buddha visited his monks.

203
00:19:55,480 --> 00:19:57,021
There were three Adahats, mind you.

204
00:19:57,061 --> 00:19:59,104
There were three fully liberated people.

205
00:19:59,124 --> 00:20:06,775
And he asks the chief monk there, how do you live in harmony with each other?

206
00:20:06,795 --> 00:20:17,328
And he said, well, every day when we wake up, when we get up, we say to ourselves, why don't I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

207
00:20:19,250 --> 00:20:22,700
Now, frankly, that only works if everybody says that.

208
00:20:25,066 --> 00:20:27,653
Otherwise, you tend to be abused.

209
00:20:31,304 --> 00:20:33,951
But you can see how that attitude, you see.

210
00:20:34,218 --> 00:20:44,852
to go to work, for instance, and to have more of an attitude of service, not like, what does the company owe me?

211
00:20:45,292 --> 00:20:48,978
But more in the sense of, what can I offer to the company?

212
00:20:48,998 --> 00:20:50,740
That doesn't undermine your rights.

213
00:20:51,320 --> 00:21:00,292
It doesn't allow you to be abused, but it's your attitude of service which undermines a lot of negativity you might have around work.

214
00:21:02,655 --> 00:21:03,938
It's the same with relationships.

215
00:21:04,441 --> 00:21:11,351
love is putting the other one first, but it's not forgetting oneself.

216
00:21:12,452 --> 00:21:16,077
That's the important point.

217
00:21:16,178 --> 00:21:24,390
I'm often asked that, you know, about, well, you know, if somebody being abused either at work or in a personal relationship,

218
00:21:24,791 --> 00:21:26,173
Should one stay there?

219
00:21:26,192 --> 00:21:44,913
Well, it's up to the person to decide, but at some point, when the abuse becomes to a level which makes no sense, and you can't get through it, and you can't get the other to see what they're doing, then often it's the best ploy just to move out.

220
00:21:46,213 --> 00:21:51,220
Or murder them.

221
00:21:51,240 --> 00:21:52,520
Or murder the other.

222
00:21:55,116 --> 00:22:02,048
So we've got this basic position of what the Buddha called delusion.

223
00:22:03,170 --> 00:22:05,493
The delusion lies in an identity.

224
00:22:06,214 --> 00:22:15,670
The identity is this body, heart and mind, this psychophysical, this human being, conventionally a human being, and we're trying to seek happiness.

225
00:22:16,111 --> 00:22:18,474
And we're seeking happiness in the world.

226
00:22:18,808 --> 00:22:20,029
And it can't deliver.

227
00:22:20,230 --> 00:22:22,953
It can't deliver because it's impermanent.

228
00:22:23,413 --> 00:22:33,125
Every time you get something which you really want and you've always wanted, the thing begins to corrode, corrupt, disappear, or somebody else nicks it.

229
00:22:34,627 --> 00:22:38,853
So we're forever chasing a dragon, you see, that doesn't actually exist.

230
00:22:40,034 --> 00:22:42,696
And what it leads us into is frustration.

231
00:22:43,117 --> 00:22:48,663
All those things that we talked about this morning to your pleasure, the frustration, the grief of loss, the fear of loss,

232
00:22:49,166 --> 00:22:53,593
and boredom, boredom that arises, and addictive behavior.

233
00:22:54,192 --> 00:22:58,858
So our practice is now to go back on that, to go back on that process.

234
00:22:58,878 --> 00:23:13,217
And the way we do it is both by developing what is beautiful in us through the practice of metta meditation, through actually looking at our lives and what we do, and beginning to see it as a service, see?

235
00:23:13,702 --> 00:23:28,721
And on the negative side, to begin to undermine it through this process of not indulging those desires, which we see at Ron Olson.

236
00:23:28,740 --> 00:23:29,721
And we've learned the trick.

237
00:23:30,083 --> 00:23:39,374
The trick is to be fully aware, to let the desire come up with all its energy, and just to stay with it and wait for it to exhaust itself.

238
00:23:39,394 --> 00:23:40,555
It's as simple as that.

239
00:23:42,037 --> 00:24:11,335
but of course the difficulty is that you have to keep doing it and that's the meaning of renunciation in Buddhism so again we make this distinction between self-mortification and renunciation so remember when the Buddha joined the well practiced seemingly as the Jains do it was more of getting rid of this physical world getting rid of this body in order that the soul might be released he didn't find that particularly helpful

240
00:24:11,887 --> 00:24:14,453
But he didn't give up on the idea of renunciation.

241
00:24:14,775 --> 00:24:17,883
So renunciation is giving something up to see how to attach to it.

242
00:24:20,650 --> 00:24:25,442
To see how we become emotionally attached to something.

243
00:24:30,484 --> 00:24:46,553
I mean, the normal, I mean, I know most of you have heard this, but the normal thing I say to people is, you know, just to, everybody has a favourite programme on telly and you sort of get your mug of coffee and your biscuit and you sit in the chair, you see, and you...

244
00:24:46,532 --> 00:24:48,595
And you don't turn the TV on.

245
00:24:48,615 --> 00:24:51,439
You just look at the screen.

246
00:24:52,420 --> 00:24:54,583
And you know it's the last of the series.

247
00:24:56,044 --> 00:24:56,404
That's a good one.

248
00:24:56,424 --> 00:24:59,087
It really is a fantastic one to try on yourself.

249
00:24:59,808 --> 00:25:01,269
You don't want to get too masochistic.

250
00:25:02,711 --> 00:25:07,817
But what it does, what it manifests for us is this incredible attachment.

251
00:25:07,837 --> 00:25:12,324
And remember that we don't actually know the strength of these attachments until we lose them.

252
00:25:13,105 --> 00:25:14,346
That's the

253
00:25:17,329 --> 00:25:36,299
So this whole business of identity is undermined through beginning to understand that we are constantly in relationship, we're constantly moving in relationship with the world around us.

254
00:25:38,423 --> 00:26:04,751
practice of vipassana is really to dig deep down into that point of identity and that's what I was saying this morning about making everything an object so when when physical pain comes when emotional and any emotional state comes happiness unhappiness physical state of pleasantness pleasure is to actually begin to look at it closely using

255
00:26:05,390 --> 00:26:16,308
And to begin to sense that there's a separation there between the knowing, between that which is doing the investigation, investigating, and that which is being investigated.

256
00:26:17,731 --> 00:26:22,420
And to recognize that the perceiver, that which is perceiving, can't be the perceiver.

257
00:26:23,362 --> 00:26:38,586
Now, as that gap becomes much more clear to us, as we begin to feel that gap more, the separation between the knowing and what is being experienced, you see,

258
00:26:38,566 --> 00:26:48,819
It's as though the knowing is beginning to understand its own quality, its own peculiar being, you might say.

259
00:26:48,839 --> 00:27:03,681
Now, for those of you for whom that's clear, remember, the sense of self-awareness, the sense of the observer, the feeler, is still something that you're perceiving.

260
00:27:04,080 --> 00:27:05,383
You can't be that either.

261
00:27:07,220 --> 00:27:11,125
And it's turning towards the feeling of the observer.

262
00:27:12,047 --> 00:27:12,887
The feeling of it.

263
00:27:13,608 --> 00:27:15,791
The feeling of presence.

264
00:27:15,811 --> 00:27:19,778
And the peculiar thing is that it's pointing in the right direction.

265
00:27:22,741 --> 00:27:24,845
It's just like when you look into a mirror.

266
00:27:25,425 --> 00:27:27,568
You're looking at your face in the mirror.

267
00:27:28,390 --> 00:27:31,614
And we delude ourselves in thinking that's how people see them.

268
00:27:32,095 --> 00:27:33,497
You've all done the two-mirror trick, haven't you?

269
00:27:34,185 --> 00:27:37,271
No, you've not done the whole thing.

270
00:27:40,018 --> 00:27:49,036
You get a mirror and you look into the mirror that you're holding to see which is giving you back the image from the original mirror.

271
00:27:49,537 --> 00:27:53,223
So when you look at the mirror, you're looking at your face the other way around.

272
00:27:54,082 --> 00:27:58,627
So to turn it round and to see how people really see you is a real shock.

273
00:28:02,053 --> 00:28:06,138
But you didn't think your nose was quite so bent.

274
00:28:06,538 --> 00:28:07,840
So it's really worth doing.

275
00:28:07,861 --> 00:28:12,968
And what that's telling us is, in this observer, you see, that the feeling of the observer

276
00:28:12,948 --> 00:28:19,740
is a sense of presence, but it's a mirror image of the Buddha within.

277
00:28:20,862 --> 00:28:23,606
And so it's actually looking in the right direction.

278
00:28:24,288 --> 00:28:35,428
So that sense of presence is telling us that there is something which is permanent, which is not born, not dying, doesn't die, and all the rest of it.

279
00:28:36,032 --> 00:28:52,273
Now, it's a bit unfortunate these days because, especially with neuroscience, I'm sure you've come across, some of you know what's happening in Buddhism, is this whole movement of secular Buddhism.

280
00:28:53,035 --> 00:29:02,866
A lot of it is based on neurobiology, which in a sense reduces everything to the brain, reduces everything to

281
00:29:04,450 --> 00:29:09,215
to neurons and ultimately to subatomic particles, I presume.

282
00:29:09,375 --> 00:29:25,175
And that as you see the brain working, even though the neurobiologists can't feel what you're feeling, so if you feel angry, certain parts of the brain light up, there's a presumption there.

283
00:29:26,017 --> 00:29:31,804
which is a leap of faith, that actually what you're measuring or what you're seeing is an emotion.

284
00:29:32,785 --> 00:29:37,490
Whereas in Buddhist psychology, what you're seeing is the effect of the mind on matter.

285
00:29:39,532 --> 00:29:50,144
The mind in the Buddhist teaching is something separate from, but still has the quality of impermanence, etc., but can actually exist outside this physical frame.

286
00:29:50,164 --> 00:29:55,872
And that is, what you get is a disbelief in that completely.

287
00:29:56,542 --> 00:30:08,424
and the body and mind are all based upon the brain and that therefore consciousness itself is just an epi, what do they call it, an emergent property.

288
00:30:08,444 --> 00:30:19,125
So there's a lot of people who are now in Buddhism who take that as their basic understanding but it's very difficult to hold that position if you read the scriptures.

289
00:30:19,814 --> 00:30:25,054
And one book that you might like to get, you can get a PDF of it.

290
00:30:25,695 --> 00:30:26,720
You can write down the writing.

291
00:30:26,740 --> 00:30:27,983
You might be able to get a copy.

292
00:30:28,486 --> 00:30:31,376
So you get a PDF of it and put it on your e-reader.

293
00:30:31,711 --> 00:30:51,911
is a book called The Island, which has been a collection of quotes from the scriptures put together by Venerable Amaro, you know, Ajahn Amaro, who's the chief monk now at Amarwati, and Pasano, who's the chief monk in America, Abugiri in California.

294
00:30:52,692 --> 00:30:59,337
And they were tackling this problem, you see, of really

295
00:30:59,892 --> 00:31:09,125
from one point of view, of undermining the teaching of the Buddha about there is something which is not conditioned.

296
00:31:09,144 --> 00:31:19,038
And I can't see how they get themselves into that position, frankly, even in my lack of knowledge about the scriptures.

297
00:31:19,058 --> 00:31:28,853
So, in that process of vipassana, we are beginning to distinguish between that which is arising and passing away

298
00:31:29,255 --> 00:31:35,020
that which is moving constantly within that inner vision, and something which is observing it.

299
00:31:36,482 --> 00:31:54,480
Now, there comes a point when you are close enough to that process, where what you begin to see is that consciousness itself, the process of being conscious, is not continuous.

300
00:31:55,402 --> 00:31:58,164
It arises and passes away, just like that.

301
00:31:58,938 --> 00:32:11,239
So then you realize that, you see, the world we're living in is completely being manufactured by us on minimal data coming in from the world.

302
00:32:11,259 --> 00:32:23,140
So if you've seen these pictures, if you've seen how the eye moves around the picture that we're looking at, how it picks up, how it's constantly moving, and we're completely unaware of it.

303
00:32:23,778 --> 00:32:33,210
Because as the eye moves quite automatically around, picking up, picking up this, it's coming into this brain-mind complex.

304
00:32:33,631 --> 00:32:35,913
And what we're seeing is put on a screen.

305
00:32:36,334 --> 00:32:38,036
That screen is consciousness.

306
00:32:38,537 --> 00:32:44,284
All this information is, to me, it's virtually like a television or a monitor.

307
00:32:44,865 --> 00:32:47,067
All that information is coming through the electrics.

308
00:32:47,285 --> 00:32:56,816
And what we're aware of only is not all the stuff that's going on behind there, but only what's actually on the screen in front of us.

309
00:32:56,836 --> 00:33:07,867
And when you begin to recognize that, you see, then you realize that the world that we're actually living in is the world I'm manufacturing.

310
00:33:07,887 --> 00:33:11,251
When I say I, I mean this psychophysical organism.

311
00:33:12,212 --> 00:33:14,355
So in the universe, there's no light.

312
00:33:15,095 --> 00:33:17,038
There are photons, but there's no light.

313
00:33:17,699 --> 00:33:21,045
You have to have a retina, you have to have a sense base in order to perceive light.

314
00:33:21,625 --> 00:33:24,230
There's no sounds in the universe, completely silent.

315
00:33:24,630 --> 00:33:29,198
You have to have the mechanism of hearing in order to hear.

316
00:33:29,218 --> 00:33:31,922
And that's our sensing body.

317
00:33:32,162 --> 00:33:33,865
And our sensing body is limited.

318
00:33:34,625 --> 00:33:36,849
We don't have the sense of smell of a dog.

319
00:33:39,766 --> 00:33:46,388
We don't have that clarity of hearing that some of the animals have.

320
00:33:46,409 --> 00:33:50,784
Our range of perception is limited by our sensibility.

321
00:33:50,804 --> 00:33:52,509
We can't see ultraviolet rays.

322
00:33:55,865 --> 00:33:57,868
But some animals can.

323
00:33:58,230 --> 00:34:06,046
Some animals have that magnetism in their head that they can actually feel where they are.

324
00:34:06,467 --> 00:34:08,231
In fact, some human beings have that.

325
00:34:08,251 --> 00:34:10,474
I met a man who came to help us.

326
00:34:10,494 --> 00:34:14,143
Just out of the blue, he came to help us put up a cootie, this hut that we have.

327
00:34:14,393 --> 00:34:26,391
And no matter which way you twisted him, you could turn him in any way you wanted to, eventually he would point to north, magnetic north, within a degree.

328
00:34:27,273 --> 00:34:31,398
Figure that.

329
00:34:31,418 --> 00:34:36,405
Now I know that when I go out walking, it's always the opposite to what I'm thinking I'm doing.

330
00:34:36,427 --> 00:34:38,329
Yeah, pathetic.

331
00:34:38,349 --> 00:34:43,336
So these sensibilities are entirely dependent upon this body, heart and mind.

332
00:34:44,110 --> 00:34:50,697
And when we begin to realize that, you see, then, of course, you take an interest in yourself.

333
00:34:50,717 --> 00:34:52,340
You take an interest in your psychology.

334
00:34:52,860 --> 00:34:58,869
You begin to realize that, actually, you're the only one who's going to take any real interest in your psychology.

335
00:35:00,550 --> 00:35:07,099
And that you're the one who's creating the mess, and you're the one who can get out of it.

336
00:35:07,860 --> 00:35:11,804
So I know that in...

337
00:35:12,949 --> 00:35:17,735
You see, remember that the Buddha said that he was completely liberated from suffering.

338
00:35:17,994 --> 00:35:19,235
He wasn't liberated from the body.

339
00:35:19,856 --> 00:35:21,478
He had a body and he suffered.

340
00:35:21,498 --> 00:35:26,324
And he died of gastroenteritis or something.

341
00:35:27,485 --> 00:35:39,496
So because he did it, he then, as it were, in the literal, in the phrase of the scriptures, he opened up the gates, the gates of the Dharma of him wide open.

342
00:35:41,097 --> 00:35:49,429
And so it means that we ourselves now are in the process of reaching that particular liberation, that libana.

343
00:35:49,449 --> 00:35:50,532
Now,

344
00:35:51,255 --> 00:35:54,440
Nirvana, in the East, you know, you don't get much talked about Nirvana.

345
00:35:54,460 --> 00:35:55,420
It's sort of presumed.

346
00:35:55,661 --> 00:35:57,423
Nobody really talks about it.

347
00:35:57,563 --> 00:36:04,273
You only talk about the path, about the practice, about the teaching that we ever talked about, about the ultimate.

348
00:36:04,713 --> 00:36:08,637
In a sense, because in the culture, it's just presumed.

349
00:36:09,259 --> 00:36:20,452
But for us, it's a very, it can be a very strange understanding that there is a level of being which has nothing at all to do with this phenomenal world.

350
00:36:20,989 --> 00:36:39,706
completely outside it it is completely unconditioned it is inherent it has its own inherent to go back to the original question it has its own inherent existence and is not dependent on the world that's the teaching

351
00:36:40,784 --> 00:36:44,092
Now the Buddha wouldn't go beyond that particular statement.

352
00:36:44,172 --> 00:36:46,277
He wouldn't get into metaphysics.

353
00:36:46,317 --> 00:36:54,436
He wouldn't get into infer that therefore there must be some sort of big being.

354
00:36:54,456 --> 00:36:55,719
So there's no creator God.

355
00:36:55,739 --> 00:36:57,342
There's nobody who's judging us.

356
00:36:57,362 --> 00:36:58,505
All that's done within us.

357
00:36:59,532 --> 00:37:02,235
And the process of liberation is entirely up to us.

358
00:37:02,717 --> 00:37:07,083
Not that people can't guide us and help us, but eventually it's us that has to sit on the cushion.

359
00:37:07,684 --> 00:37:08,666
We have to do the work.

360
00:37:09,746 --> 00:37:15,916
And the process of liberation comes about through our own particular effort.

361
00:37:15,936 --> 00:37:16,317
That's all.

362
00:37:16,737 --> 00:37:18,159
Nobody can do it for us.

363
00:37:18,179 --> 00:37:21,344
So, you know, like they say in Zen, the Buddha can only point to the moon.

364
00:37:22,746 --> 00:37:23,568
I'll get you over there.

365
00:37:25,411 --> 00:37:28,375
So, this nirvana that we're moving towards

366
00:37:29,148 --> 00:37:30,896
It's described in various ways.

367
00:37:32,461 --> 00:37:36,961
Now, the usual way that he prefers is negative.

368
00:37:37,242 --> 00:37:38,769
It's not born, doesn't die.

369
00:37:40,032 --> 00:37:45,420
And the word he uses there is a Pali word which translates as exists.

370
00:37:45,780 --> 00:37:50,788
There's another Pali word which is like our is, like this is a statue.

371
00:37:50,829 --> 00:37:52,731
So the is there has virtually no meaning.

372
00:37:53,532 --> 00:37:57,659
But if you say that statue exists, that gives it a different twist on itself.

373
00:37:57,679 --> 00:38:00,943
There exists that which is not born, doesn't die.

374
00:38:01,224 --> 00:38:08,114
And he says, if it did not exist, there'd be no escape from what is born, dies, is created, is conditioned.

375
00:38:08,601 --> 00:38:09,382
It's quite clear.

376
00:38:09,744 --> 00:38:11,465
He talks about an ayatana.

377
00:38:11,766 --> 00:38:15,672
Ayatana here is the word that means a sphere of experience.

378
00:38:16,193 --> 00:38:20,498
So we have six ayatana.

379
00:38:20,518 --> 00:38:22,621
The sphere of seeing, you see.

380
00:38:22,641 --> 00:38:25,326
Can't be confused with the sphere of hearing.

381
00:38:25,425 --> 00:38:29,572
They're two different ways of experiencing the universe.

382
00:38:29,592 --> 00:38:33,177
Then there's tasting, smelling, and all the meditation that goes on.

383
00:38:33,978 --> 00:38:37,342
Then he says that there is a sphere where there's none of it.

384
00:38:38,452 --> 00:38:43,699
where there's no moon, there's no sun, there's no coming, there's no going, there's no staying, there's no time.

385
00:38:47,483 --> 00:38:48,826
Very clear statements.

386
00:38:48,846 --> 00:39:06,266
And then when it comes to a more positive way, he's got something like 32 adjectives trying to point to it, such as something that we say when we repeat, a refuge, a home, an island, an island that you cannot go beyond.

387
00:39:08,271 --> 00:39:12,081
So the island is something completely separate from the landmass.

388
00:39:12,101 --> 00:39:12,742
And that's it.

389
00:39:12,782 --> 00:39:13,704
You can't go beyond it.

390
00:39:14,465 --> 00:39:18,074
How can we get a glimpse of that in our practice?

391
00:39:18,434 --> 00:39:20,780
How can we begin to see it?

392
00:39:20,820 --> 00:39:22,764
Because this is what we're supposed to be.

393
00:39:22,804 --> 00:39:24,829
Not becoming.

394
00:39:25,130 --> 00:39:27,815
The I is always becoming some other person.

395
00:39:28,184 --> 00:39:34,936
Even during the day, you might change from being a mother, a father, to a workmate, and so on and so forth.

396
00:39:34,956 --> 00:39:38,963
So your personality, your person, your personhood is constantly shifting and changing.

397
00:39:39,704 --> 00:39:42,688
But here's the something which doesn't do that.

398
00:39:42,708 --> 00:39:43,610
It's beyond change.

399
00:39:45,041 --> 00:40:04,653
So, in our practice, you see, when you're observing things and you get more and more a distinct sense of being the self, being the observer, being the feeler, you see, and making that clear to yourself, and sometimes perhaps turning into that sense of presence that's there.

